text: Best part of the trailer..... In bed she says "dont ruin my childhood"  I actually think this film, with this lead actor may actually remind us all of how truly amazing that show and that part of our childhood was. Even older kids who viewed it as cheesy and over the top "good" still would find themselves engrossed. We need more of this pure kindness, pure positivity, pure growth messaging to our youth these days. I long for the days when a show like Mr. Roger's Neighborhood was in a kids constant rotation. Along with shows like Reading Rainbow. It's our fault kids won't watch this stuff anymore, we caved in and started feeding them garbage instead.   High Hopes for this film.

text: I remember when Mr. Rogers came to Sesame Street and taught Big Bird about real and pretend (it was an episode where Snuffalupagus was still Big Bird's imaginary friend. I never once got the impression he was being condescending or lacking in patience. He was very kind and made sure Big Bird understood what he was teaching him. When I was a child, I spent a lot of time in hospitals having surgeries. I didn't have many friends. Mr. Rogers and his imaginative world became my friend. I liked following the little train into the imagination world because it made me forget my own for awhile and I could be happy. I will echo what the woman in the trailer said....DON'T you DARE ruin my childhood. I do think Tom Hanks is absolutely the best choice to play this good friend though. I can think of no one better.

text: I am 49 years of age, but every time I see a video clip or old episode of Mr. Rogers, I cry. Why? Because, growing up in the late 70's through 80's Mr. Rogers warmed my heart & soul. I didn't fit in with my peers at school or in the neighborhood. My relationship with my Mother during that time wasn't the best either. I felt like a loser/ugly/dumb/etc! But when his show was on, I felt special and loved. I didn't know at the time he was a Presbyterian Pastor. Over the years I visited many Churches (denominations). The one denomination to me that has the most giving/caring/loving spirit are the the Presbyterians. You could tell at first glance MR. ROGERS HAD A GENUINE SINCERE HUMBLE SPIRIT ABOUT HIM. I LOOK FORWARD TO SEEING YOU THIS MOVIE!!! REST IN PEACE SIR!!!!

text: I'm 49 and many of the lessons I've learned from watching Mr. Rogers have been applicable in my daily life. I loved the time I spent with him and wept when I learned of his passing. Watching the documentary about his life last year really opened my eyes as to how much he loved and was loved. My favorite part of that was 143.   That's out of the way. Now, Tom Hanks is a fine actor and an upstanding man. I suppose you just have to get past your disbelief and allow a little poetic license because their voices definitely aren't similar.  I think the important thing to take away from this is the emotion and the beauty of trying to portray someone who surely would have been canonized had he been in  a different time and place.   I will make a point of seeing this in a theater. It'll be the only movie I'll pay to see this year.

text: Mr Rogers one of the few truly rare celebrities that was 100% authentic.  when the world around him was full of racial tension he had an episode where he offered a black friend to come over and soak his feed in the kiddie pool with him on a hot day.   he didn't scream and shout at the injustice around him, he quietly showed though kindness and compassion the right way to act.   if you watch early episodes he didn't speak when taking off his shoes. after receiving a fan letter about a blind child that loves his show but didn't always know what he was doing (as closed captioning wasn't a thing) Mr Rogers would try to avoid empty air by describing what he was doing "i'm taking off my right shoe now.  i'm putting on my other shoe now.. "etc   .  mr rogers responded to every single fan mail he received with a hand written letter, or thank you note.  not printed, not typed and not written by someone else. because he believed if someone spent the time to write to him, they deserved the same respect in return.  there are many many stories like this, you wont find dirt if you look into Mr Rogers. may he rip.

text: OK. I like that they got Tom Hanks for this, but his timing on the song was WAY off. And, seeing this reminds Me of a question I've always had about the show: Why in the world did Mr. Rogers change shoes when he came into the house? I mean, I can understand putting away his jacket or sweater-vest when he came in, because he was inside, but his shoes? If you're trying to pretend the guy is in his own house, why wouldn't he put on slippers or just go with socks, if he doesn't go barefoot? Or, if it's trying to act like you're a guest in his home, wouldn't he leave the dress shoes on instead? Because changing one's shoes is NOT something I'VE ever heard be a thing to do when you have guests over. Maybe before they get there, but not WHILE they're THERE. And that's another thing: why did the Mr. Rogers' show always start out with him coming inside? If you're a guest, wouldn't YOU be the one coming in? And we know it's "his" house because he puts his stuff away & it's his shoes on the floor - two things you wouldn't have if you were going to somebody else's place - so it's not like you could say the show was about somebody always asking Mr. Rogers to come over or something. In short, that show was VERY confusing, on a lot of levels. (And not just the acid trip required to believe a tiny model tram car can connect reality to that make-believe weirdness that was in every episode, either - & I even remember Mr. Rogers going in there a time or two, as well!)

text: The formula is that said writer, we'll call him Dan, is sent in by a magazine to write a hit piece.  Dan is enamored with the pure Fred Rogers, always optimistic, always serving.  One day Dan tells about how when he was a kid, his dad could never come to his little league games because he had to work long hours in the factory to feed the family.  Then came the championships, and the dad took a whole day off work just for him... but never showed up‚Äîbecause he was killed by an angry mob after MLK was assassinated.  And that's why he became a reporter, to stick it to bad people, politicians, economic abusers, slumlords...  Fred empathizes, then asks if he can be his new dad and gives him an old Daniel Tiger puppet to cement some metaphor.  Dan becomes good and shadows Fred and all the kind things he does.  Meanwhile, Dan keeps ignoring calls from his bosses, who leave voicemails saying "if you don't have some dirt on our desk by next Friday, you're fired!"  All is well, but then a kid from the hospital dies and Dan relapses and disappears, turning in a scathing expose of Mr. Rogers, how he gives people false hope in an ultimately dreary world, and by making people feel calm and loved kept people from getting angry and actually solving their problems proactively.  In effect Mr. Roger's Neighborhood elongated Vietnam/Civil Rights/Nixon/etc, making him complicit _at best_.  Dan's girlfriend breaks up with him, saying they used to be so idealistic when they first met, and Dan responds with a speech about "the real world isn't all friendly neighbors and cable cars mislabeled as trolleys." [Yeah, he said it!] He throws the puppet in the trash, ruining it.  Dan goes on a binge spree, living up the media sell-out life, but inwardly feels sad that he threw a good man under the bus and now can't contain the monster he created, having scandalized Fred's name.  He quits his job and apologizes to Mr. Rogers, who quickly forgives him, tells of when he once was tempted to give up but didn't, and says "go get 'em Daniel Tiger!," sending Dan to catch his girlfriend's flight.  Cut to an epilogue about how Mr. Rogers just died and that made Dan remember that epiphanical assignment, his now wife and three kids, and that moment he decided to become an award-winning children's book author.  Pan to the Daniel Tiger puppet on the mantle, next to a picture of him and his dad in baseball uniforms, an fade to black...

text: Looks like another addition to a great season of biopics. I would very much like Hollywood to do one  on Jared Fogle, the former Subway spokesperson and now convicted felon,  roly-poly-boy-toy and daily punching bag for any number of his fellow inmates at the federal penitentiary in Englewood, Colorado.     Perhaps it could be a musical.   One of the numbers could be called "Smaller Pants," and two different versions could both open and close the production.  In the beginning, Jared sings "I wanna get in smaller pants," in reference to his desire to lose weight by eating only veggie subs.  At the end prior to his arrest, as he's flying around the country molesting children, he could sing the same line, but it would of course have a far more sinister meaning.     Another number could involve a couple of parents going to the authorities to report that their pre-adolescent son has been victimized by Fogle.  The song could be titled "He Went to Jared."     You see, I'm a dead ringer for Fogle.   We're talking "separated at birth" identical.   Up until November, 2015 I had a fairly steady part time gig posing as him and entertaining at kids' birthday parties.  For a reasonable fee, I'd provide the entertainment (balloon animals and showing the kids the former pants with a 48 inch waistline that "Jared" used to have to wear before he started eating Subway veggies subs everyday) and the food (a Subway platter). Needless to say, my tax returns for the past few years have shown a fairly significant reduction in income. My last gig was just after Thanksgiving in 2015. The people who had booked me had paid a deposit in advance, so they went ahead and had me come out with my balloons and five foot cold cut with six toppings on  Italian herb bread.  I ended up getting mauled by their German Shepherd who had been watching CNN a week or so earlier.

There is a reason why Mr. Rogers would genuinely get to know chauffeurs and taxi drivers and waiters and everyone he met. There's a reason why he genuinely loved everyone he came in contact with. There's a reason why he would call a random person he met out of the blue and tell them happy birthday on their birthday. That reason?  The man had a unbelievable faith in our Lord Jesus Christ. He was a pastor, and he was using the love of Jesus given to him by the Holy Spirit to spread that love and he did. People often claimed that he was the nicest person in the world and he was so nice he was hard to interview because he would genuinely want to know about the interviewer and ask them questions and ask their opinions. He was the nicest person because he allowed the love of Christ to shine in him.  He prayed every single day for hours and hours for his family and his fans and the world. I truly hope that this movie does not gloss over the fact that this incredible man was incredible because of his faith and because of his love for Jesus and the love of Jesus shining in him.

text: I used to live in a very bad neighborhood in LA until I moved to Maryland but unfortunately I felt like I still wanted to exists. I wanted people to notice me and feel acknowledged let alone I felt I was made fun of and never feel wanted when I was younger. I‚Äôve done a lot of bad things and I felt angry and depressed. I will admit this because I feel extremely guilty I was looking for the Mr. Roger show and when I couldn‚Äôt find his show again I got even sad and angry and felt like he abandoned me like everyone else until years later like now when I first watched this trailer I got goosebumps. I swear to you all my heart was beating fast and I teared up a little. We all looked up to him like a friend, brother, and a father figure. Anyways I did my research on him on why did he stop making the show and that‚Äôs when my answer and my curiosity finally sprung. I felt awful and I know his death was a long time ago but to me it felt like yesterday. I literally prayed to god and told the great lord to tell him I‚Äôm sorry and that I failed him in past and wish I could‚Äôve done differently and to also look after his soul. This man changed me every time I was down and whenever I wanted to learn something he was there in the tube with great heavenly vibes. He is forever one of my guardian angels.
